<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Verb">Verb</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=run&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Verb"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg/220px-Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg/330px-Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg/440px-Flickr_cc_runner_wisconsin_u.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1950" data-file-height="1301"></a><figcaption>A runner running (<a href="#English:_race">sense 1.4</a>)</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><span><span class="mw-tmh-player video"><video id="mwe_player_3_placeholder" poster="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/100_m_female_Athletissima_2012.ogv/220px--100_m_female_Athletissima_2012.ogv.jpg" preload="none" class="mw-file-element" width="220" height="124" data-durationhint="20" data-mwtitle="100_m_female_Athletissima_2012.ogv" data-mwprovider="wikimediacommons" resource="/wiki/File:100_m_female_Athletissima_2012.ogv" playsinline="" disabled="disabled" tabindex="-1" style="aspect-ratio: 220 / 124;"></video><a class="mw-tmh-play" href="/wiki/File:100_m_female_Athletissima_2012.ogv" title="Play video" role="button"><span class="mw-tmh-play-icon"></span></a></span></span><a href="/wiki/File:100_m_female_Athletissima_2012.ogv" class="mw-file-magnify"></a><figcaption>Women running (<a href="#English:_race">sense 1.4</a>) in a 100-meter foot race</figcaption></figure>
<p><span class="headword-line"><strong class="Latn headword" lang="en">run</strong> (<i>third-person singular simple present</i> <b class="Latn form-of lang-en s-verb-form-form-of" lang="en"><a href="/wiki/runs#English" title="runs">runs</a></b>, <i>present participle</i> <b class="Latn form-of lang-en ing-form-form-of" lang="en"><a href="/wiki/running#English" title="running">running</a></b>, <i>simple past</i> <b class="Latn form-of lang-en spast-form-of" lang="en"><a href="/wiki/ran#English" title="ran">ran</a></b>, <i>past participle</i> <b class="Latn form-of lang-en past|part-form-of" lang="en"><strong class="selflink">run</strong></b>)</span>
</p>
<ol><li>To move swiftly.
<ol><li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/move#English" title="move">move</a> forward <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/quickly#English" title="quickly">quickly</a> upon <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/two#English" title="two">two</a> <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/feet#English" title="feet">feet</a> by alternately making a short <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/jump#English" title="jump">jump</a> off either foot. <span class="ib-brac qualifier-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content qualifier-content">Compare <i><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/walk#English" title="walk">walk</a></i>.</span><span class="ib-brac qualifier-brac">)</span>
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en"><b>Run</b>, Sarah, <b>run</b>!</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1967</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Sleigh" class="extiw" title="w:Barbara Sleigh">Barbara Sleigh</a>, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessamy" class="extiw" title="w:Jessamy">Jessamy</a></cite>, Sevenoaks, Kent: Bloomsbury, published <span class="None" lang="und">1993</span>, <small><a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0_340_19547_9" title="Special:BookSources/0 340 19547 9">→ISBN</a></small>, page <span class="None" lang="und">122</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Through the open front door <b>ran</b> Jessamy, down the steps to where Kitto was sitting at the bottom with the pram beside him.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><span class="see-cites">For more quotations using this term, see <a href="/wiki/Citations:run#English" title="Citations:run">Citations:run</a>.</span></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/go#English" title="go">go</a> at a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/fast#English" title="fast">fast</a> pace; to move <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/quickly#English" title="quickly">quickly</a>.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">I have been <b>running</b> all over the building looking for him.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Sorry, I've got to <b>run</b>; my house is on fire.</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1965</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_Cobb" class="extiw" title="w:Ed Cobb">Ed Cobb</a>, “<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tainted_Love" class="extiw" title="w:Tainted Love">Tainted Love</a>”, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Stop_Erotic_Cabaret" class="extiw" title="w:Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret">Non-Stop Erotic Cabaret</a></cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XZVpR3Pk-r8">[1]</a></sup>, performed by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soft_Cell" class="extiw" title="w:Soft Cell">Soft Cell</a>, published <span class="None" lang="und">1981</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Once I <b>ran</b> to you (I ran) / Now I <b>run</b> from you / This tainted love you've given / I give you all a boy could give you</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/cause#English" title="cause">cause</a> to move <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/quickly#English" title="quickly">quickly</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/lightly#English" title="lightly">lightly</a>.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Every day I <b>run</b> my dog across the field and back.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">I'll just <b>run</b> the vacuum cleaner over the carpet.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en"><b>Run</b> your fingers through my hair.</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1912</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Conan_Doyle" class="extiw" title="w:Arthur Conan Doyle">Arthur Conan Doyle</a>, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lost_World_(Doyle_novel)" class="extiw" title="w:The Lost World (Doyle novel)">The Lost World<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Being an Account of the Recent Amazing Adventures of Professor George E. Challenger, Lord John Roxton, Professor Summerlee, and Mr. E. D. Malone of the “Daily Gazette.”">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></a></cite>, London, New York, N.Y.: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hodder_%26_Stoughton" class="extiw" title="w:Hodder &amp; Stoughton">Hodder and Stoughton</a>, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/1029993343">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Challenger and I <b>ran</b> Summerlee along, one at each of his elbows, while Lord John covered our retreat, firing again and again as savage heads snarled at us out of the bushes.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li class="mw-empty-elt"></li><li class="senseid" id="English:_race" data-senseid="race"> <span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a> or <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/compete#English" title="compete">compete</a> in a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/race#English" title="race">race</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The horse will <b>run</b> in the Preakness next year.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">I'm not ready to <b>run</b> a marathon.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/transport#English" title="transport">transport</a> (someone or something), notionally at a brisk pace.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Could you <b>run</b> me over to the store?</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Please <b>run</b> this report upstairs to director's office.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> Of a means of transportation: to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/travel#English" title="travel">travel</a> (a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/route#English" title="route">route</a>).
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><i>the bus (train, plane, ferry boat, etc) <b>runs</b> between Newport and Riverside</i></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1997</b></span>, Karl-Heinz Reger, Nelles Verlag Staff, <cite>Malaysia - Singapore - Brunei</cite>, Hunter Publishing, Inc, <small><a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9783886189021" title="Special:BookSources/9783886189021">→ISBN</a></small>, page <span class="None" lang="und">91</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Small planes <b>run</b> between Alor and Langkawi. BUS: Express busses leave the bus terminal on the corner of Jl. Langgar and Jl. Stesyen for K. Kedah, <span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b">[</span>…<span class="q-hellip-b">]</span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><b>2013</b> April 15, Mary Ann Sternberg, <cite>Along the River Road: Past and Present on Louisiana's Historic Byway</cite>, LSU Press, <small><a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780807150634" title="Special:BookSources/9780807150634">→ISBN</a></small>, page <span class="None" lang="und">62</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">The first steam ferry or tug, the Little Minnie, <b>ran</b> the river in the 1870s. When vehicles were to cross, a barge was affixed to the Minnie to carry them.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/transit#English" title="transit">transit</a> a length of a river, as in <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/whitewater_rafting#English" title="whitewater rafting">whitewater rafting</a>.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1979</b></span>, United States. Forest Service. Rocky Mountain Region, <cite>Piedra River: Final Environmental Impact Statement &amp; Wild &amp; Scenic River Study</cite>, page <span class="None" lang="und">74</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">To put it frankly, if you people had to hire others to run the river and survey it for you, if, in short, you can't even <b>run</b> it yourself, why do think you can decide who is and who is not competent? River running, as has been<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b">[</span>…<span class="q-hellip-b">]</span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> Of fish, to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/migrate#English" title="migrate">migrate</a> for <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/spawning#English" title="spawning">spawning</a>.</li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/American_football#English" title="American football">American football</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a> or <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To carry (a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/football#English" title="football">football</a>) down the field, as opposed to passing or kicking.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><b>2019</b> December 29, Chad Finn, “24 thoughts on the Patriots’ loss to the Dolphins”, in <cite>Boston Globe</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2019/12/29/patriots-dolphins-recap-thoughts-analysis">[2]</a></sup>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Then, on their second possession, Isaiah Ford <b>ran</b> for 11 yards after abandoning a flea flicker.  [...] The Patriots <b>ran</b> the ball just 27 times despite averaging 5 yards per carry.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="maintenance-line" style="color: #777777;">(<span id="rfd-sense-notice-en-"></span>Should we <a href="/wiki/Wiktionary:Requests_for_deletion/English#run" title="Wiktionary:Requests for deletion/English">delete</a><sup class="plainlinks">(<a class="external text" href="https://en.wiktionary.org/w/index.php?title=Wiktionary:Requests_for_deletion/English&amp;action=edit&amp;section=new&amp;preload=Template:rfd-sense/preload&amp;preloadtitle=%5B%5Brun%23rfd-sense-notice-en-%7crun%5D%5D">+</a>)</sup> this sense?)</span> <span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To achieve or perform by running or as if by running.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The horse <b>ran</b> a great race.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/flee#English" title="flee">flee</a> from a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/danger#English" title="danger">danger</a> or towards help.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Whenever things get tough, she cuts and <b>runs</b>.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">When he's broke, he <b>runs</b> to me for money.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#figurative" title="Appendix:Glossary">figurative</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/pass#English" title="pass">pass</a> (without <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/stop#English" title="stop">stopping</a>), typically a stop <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/signal#English" title="signal">signal</a>, <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/stop_sign#English" title="stop sign">stop sign</a><span class="serial-comma">,</span> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/duty#English" title="duty">duty</a> to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/yield#English" title="yield">yield</a> the <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/right_of_way#English" title="right of way">right of way</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">If you have a collision with a vehicle oncoming from the right, after having <b>run</b> priority to the right, you are at fault.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/juggling#Noun" title="juggling">juggling</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#colloquial" title="Appendix:Glossary">colloquial</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To juggle a pattern <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/continuously#English" title="continuously">continuously</a>, as opposed to starting and stopping quickly.</li></ol></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content">fluids</span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To flow.
<ol><li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> Of a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/liquid#English" title="liquid">liquid</a>, to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/flow#English" title="flow">flow</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The river <b>runs</b> through the forest.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">There's blood <b>running</b> down your leg.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#figurative" title="Appendix:Glossary">figuratively</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To move or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/spread#English" title="spread">spread</a> quickly.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">There's a strange story <b>running</b> around the neighborhood.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The flu is <b>running</b> through my daughter's kindergarten.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> Of an object, to have a liquid <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/flow#English" title="flow">flowing</a> from it.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Your nose is <b>running</b>.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Why is the hose still <b>running</b>?</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To make a liquid flow; to make liquid flow from or into an object.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">You'll have to <b>run</b> the water a while before it gets hot.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Could you <b>run</b> a bath for me, please?</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To become <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/liquid#English" title="liquid">liquid</a>; to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/melt#English" title="melt">melt</a>.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1717</b></span> [<i><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#a." title="Appendix:Glossary"><abbr title="ante">a.</abbr></a></i> 18 <small class="ce-date"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#CE" title="Appendix:Glossary"><span title="Glossary and display preference">CE</span></a></small>], Ovid, translated by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Addison" class="extiw" title="w:Joseph Addison">Joseph Addison</a>, <cite>Ovid's Metamorphoses in fifteen books. Translated by the most eminent hands. Adorn'd with sculptures</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?cc=ecco;c=ecco;idno=004871123.0001.000;node=004871123.0001.000:6;seq=125;">[3]</a></sup>, Book the Third, The Story of <i>Narcissus</i>, page <span class="None" lang="und">92</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">As Wax dissolves, as Ice begins to <b>run</b>,</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1729</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Woodward_(naturalist)" class="extiw" title="w:John Woodward (naturalist)">John Woodward</a>, <cite>An Attempt Towards a Natural History of the Fossils of England</cite>, Tome I, page <span class="None" lang="und">223</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">The <i>Sussex</i> ores <b>run</b> pretty freely in the Fire for Iron-Ores; otherwise they would hardly be worth working.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/leak#English" title="leak">leak</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/spread#English" title="spread">spread</a> in an undesirable fashion; to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/bleed#English" title="bleed">bleed</a> (especially used of <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/dye#English" title="dye">dye</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/paint#English" title="paint">paint</a>).
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">During washing, the red from the rug <b>ran</b> onto the white sheet, staining it pink.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li>To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/fuse#English" title="fuse">fuse</a>; to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/shape#English" title="shape">shape</a>; to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/mould#English" title="mould">mould</a>; to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/cast#English" title="cast">cast</a>.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> bullets</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1718</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Felton" class="extiw" title="w:Henry Felton">Henry Felton</a>, <cite>A Dissertation on Reading the Classics, and Forming a Just Style</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5oDAAAAQAAJ&amp;pg=PA6">[4]</a></sup>, page 6:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">But, my Lord, the fairest Diamonds are rough till they are polished, and the purest Gold must be <b>run</b> and washed, and sifted in the Oar.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li></ol></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/nautical#English" title="nautical">nautical</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> of a vessel</span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To sail before the wind, in distinction from <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/reach#English" title="reach">reaching</a> or sailing <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/close-hauled#English" title="close-hauled">close-hauled</a>.</li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/control#English" title="control">control</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/manage#English" title="manage">manage</a>; to be in <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/charge#English" title="charge">charge</a> of.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">My uncle <b>ran</b> a corner store for forty years.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">She <b>runs</b> the fundraising.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">My parents think they <b>run</b> my life.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">He is <b>running</b> the candidate's expensive campaign.</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><b>1972</b> December 29, Richard Schickel, “Masterpieces underrated and overlooked”, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Life_(magazine)" class="extiw" title="w:Life (magazine)">Life</a></cite>, volume <span class="None" lang="und">73</span>, number <span class="None" lang="und">25</span>, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.ro/books?id=R1cEAAAAMBAJ&amp;pg=PA22&amp;dq=runs">page <span class="None" lang="und">22</span></a>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">A friend of mine who <b>runs</b> an intellectual magazine was grousing about his movie critic, complaining that though the fellow had liked <i>The Godfather</i> (page 58), he had neglected to label it clearly as a masterpiece.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><b>2013</b> May 11, “<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21577372-how-india-throwing-away-worlds-biggest-economic-opportunity-what-waste">What a waste</a>”, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Economist" class="extiw" title="w:The Economist">The Economist</a></cite>, volume <span class="None" lang="und">407</span>, number <span class="None" lang="und">8835</span>, page <span class="None" lang="und">12</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">India is <b>run</b> by gerontocrats and epigones: grey hairs and groomed heirs.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><span class="see-cites">For more quotations using this term, see <a href="/wiki/Citations:run#English" title="Citations:run">Citations:run</a>.</span></li></ul></li>
<li class="mw-empty-elt"></li><li class="senseid" id="English:_be_candidate" data-senseid="be candidate"><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To be a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/candidate#English" title="candidate">candidate</a> in an <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/election#English" title="election">election</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">I have decided to <b>run</b> for governor of California.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">We're trying to find somebody to <b>run</b> against him next year.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li>To make participate in certain kinds of competitions.
<ol><li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To make run in a race.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">He <b>ran</b> his best horse in the Derby.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To make run in an election.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The Green Party is <b>running</b> twenty candidates in this election.</i></div></dd></dl></li></ol></li>
<li>To exert continuous activity; to proceed.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> through life; to <b>run</b> in a circle</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To be <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/present#English" title="present">presented</a> in the <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/media#English" title="media">media</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The story will <b>run</b> on the 6-o'clock news.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The latest Robin Williams movie is <b>running</b> at the Silver City theatre.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Her picture <b>ran</b> on the front page of the newspaper.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/print#English" title="print">print</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/broadcast#English" title="broadcast">broadcast</a> in the media.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en"><b>run</b> a story; <b>run</b> an ad</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/smuggle#English" title="smuggle">smuggle</a> (<a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/illegal#English" title="illegal">illegal</a> goods).
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> guns; to <b>run</b> rum</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1728</b></span>, Jonathan Swift, “An answer to a paper, called <i>A memorial of the poor inhabitants, tradesmen, and labourers of the kingdom of Ireland</i>”, in <cite>The Works of Dr. Jonathan Swift</cite>, published <span class="None" lang="und">1757</span>, page <span class="None" lang="und">175</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">[...]whereas in the business of laying heavy impositions two and two never made more than one ; which happens by lessening the import, and the strong temptation of <b>running</b> such goods as paid high duties</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/agriculture#English" title="agriculture">agriculture</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/sort#English" title="sort">sort</a> through a large volume of <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/produce#English" title="produce">produce</a> in <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/quality_control#English" title="quality control">quality control</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Looks like we're gonna have to <b>run</b> the tomatoes again.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li>To extend or persist, statically or dynamically, through space or time.
<ol><li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/extend#English" title="extend">extend</a> in <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/space#English" title="space">space</a> or through a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/range#English" title="range">range</a> (often with a measure phrase).
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The border <b>runs</b> for 3000 miles.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The leash <b>runs</b> along a wire.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The grain of the wood <b>runs</b> to the right on this table.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">It <b>ran</b> in quality from excellent to substandard.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/extend#English" title="extend">extend</a> in <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/time#English" title="time">time</a>, to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/last#English" title="last">last</a>, to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/continue#English" title="continue">continue</a> (usually with a measure phrase).
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The sale will <b>run</b> for ten days.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The contract <b>runs</b> through 2008.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The meeting <b>ran</b> late.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The book <b>runs</b> 655 pages.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">The speech <b>runs</b> as follows: …</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To make something extend in space.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">I need to <b>run</b> this wire along the wall.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> Of a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/machine#English" title="machine">machine</a>, including computer <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/program#English" title="program">programs</a>, to be <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/operate#English" title="operate">operating</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/work#English" title="work">working</a> normally.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">My car stopped <b>running</b>.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">That computer <b>runs</b> twenty-four hours a day.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Buses don't <b>run</b> here on Sunday.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To make a machine <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/operate#English" title="operate">operate</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">It's full. You can <b>run</b> the dishwasher now.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Don't <b>run</b> the engine so fast.</i></div></dd></dl></li></ol></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/execute#English" title="execute">execute</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/carry_out#English" title="carry out">carry out</a> a <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/plan#English" title="plan">plan</a>, <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/procedure#English" title="procedure">procedure</a><span class="serial-comma">,</span> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/program#English" title="program">program</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">They <b>ran</b> twenty blood tests on me and they still don't know what's wrong.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Our coach had us <b>running</b> plays for the whole practice.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">I will <b>run</b> the sample.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Don't <b>run</b> that software unless you have permission.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">My computer is too old to <b>run</b> the new OS.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li>To pass or go quickly in thought or conversation.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> from one subject to another</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1697</b></span>, Joseph Addison, “An essay on the Georgics”, in <cite>The Works of Virgil: Containing His Pastorals, Georgics, and Aeneis</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=K3peAAAAcAAJ&amp;pg=PA44-IA13">[5]</a></sup>, by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Dryden" class="extiw" title="w:John Dryden">John Dryden</a>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en"><i>Virgil</i> was so well acquainted with this Secret, that to set off his first <i>Georgic</i>, he has <b>run</b> into a set of Precepts, which are almost foreign to his Subject,</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/copular_verb#English" title="copular verb">copulative</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To become <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/different#English" title="different">different</a> in a way mentioned (usually to become <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/worse#English" title="worse">worse</a>).
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Our supplies are <b>running</b> low.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">They frequently overspent and soon <b>ran</b> into debt.</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1712</b></span>, Joseph Addison, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cato,_a_Tragedy" class="extiw" title="w:Cato, a Tragedy">Cato, a Tragedy</a></cite>, act IV, scene i:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Have I not cause to rave, and beat my breast, / To rend my heart with grief and <b>run</b> distracted?</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1968</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Simon" class="extiw" title="w:Paul Simon">Paul Simon</a> (lyrics and music), “The Boxer”:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">I was no more than a boy / In the company of strangers / In the quiet of the railway station / <b>Running</b> scared.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><span class="see-cites">For more quotations using this term, see <a href="/wiki/Citations:run#English" title="Citations:run">Citations:run</a>.</span></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/cost#English" title="cost">cost</a> a large amount of money.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Buying a new laptop will <b>run</b> you a thousand dollars.</i></div></dd>
<dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Laptops <b>run</b> about a thousand dollars apiece.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#intransitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">intransitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> Of <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/stitches#English" title="stitches">stitches</a> or stitched clothing, to <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/unravel#English" title="unravel">unravel</a>.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">My stocking is <b>running</b>.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#transitive" title="Appendix:Glossary">transitive</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To cause stitched clothing to unravel.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><b>1977-1980</b>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lou_Sullivan" class="extiw" title="w:Lou Sullivan">Lou Sullivan</a>, personal diary, quoted in <b>2019</b>, Ellis Martin, Zach Ozma (editors), <i>We Both Laughed In Pleasure</i>
<dl><dd>He took off the nylons &amp; had <b>runned</b> one. He said "now I <i>really</i> look like a street whore!"</dd></dl></li></ul></li>
<li>To pursue in thought; to carry in contemplation.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1692</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_South" class="extiw" title="w:Robert South">Robert South</a>, “Discourse I. The creation of man in God’s image”, in <cite>Discourses on Various Subjects and Occasions</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://books.google.com/?id=-BIwAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=PA1">[6]</a></sup>, published <span class="None" lang="und">1827</span>, page 1:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">To <b>run</b> the world back to its first original and infancy, and, as it were, to view nature in its cradle,</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1695</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremy_Collier" class="extiw" title="w:Jeremy Collier">Jeremy Collier</a>, “A Thought”, in <cite>Miscellanies upon Moral Subjects by Jeremy Collier</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A33913.0001.001/1:11?rgn=div1;view=fulltext">[7]</a></sup>, page <span class="None" lang="und">88</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Methinks, if it might be, I would gladly understand the Formation of a Soul, <b>run</b> it up to its <i>Punctum Saliens</i>, and see it beat the first <i>conscious</i> Pulse.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To cause to enter; to thrust.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> a sword into or through the body; to <b>run</b> a nail into one's foot</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1814</b></span>, Sir <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Scott" class="extiw" title="w:Walter Scott">Walter Scott</a>, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waverley_(novel)" class="extiw" title="w:Waverley (novel)">Waverley</a></cite>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">“You <b>run</b> your head into the lion's mouth,” answered Mac-Ivor.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1844</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Dickens" class="extiw" title="w:Charles Dickens">Charles Dickens</a>, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Chuzzlewit" class="extiw" title="w:Martin Chuzzlewit">The Life and Adventures of Martin Chuzzlewit</a></cite>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">With that he took off his great-coat, and having <b>run</b> his fingers through his hair, thrust one hand gently in the bosom of his waistcoat</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1977</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agatha_Christie" class="extiw" title="w:Agatha Christie">Agatha Christie</a>, chapter 4, in <cite>An Autobiography</cite>, part II, London: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Collins,_Sons" class="extiw" title="w:William Collins, Sons">Collins</a>, <small><a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-00-216012-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-00-216012-4">→ISBN</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">There was also hairdressing: hairdressing, too, really was hairdressing in those times — no <b>running</b> a comb through it and that was that. It was curled, frizzed, waved, put in curlers overnight, waved with hot tongs;<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b">[</span>…<span class="q-hellip-b">]</span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span>.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><span class="see-cites">For more quotations using this term, see <a href="/wiki/Citations:run#English" title="Citations:run">Citations:run</a>.</span></li></ul></li>
<li>To drive or force; to cause, or permit, to be driven.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1611</b></span>, <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bible" class="extiw" title="w:Bible">The Holy Bible,<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Conteyning the Old Testament, and the New. Newly Translated out of the Originall Tongues: &amp; with the Former Translations Diligently Compared and Reuised, by His Maiesties Speciall Comandement. Appointed to be Read in Churches.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></a></cite> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_James_Version" class="extiw" title="w:King James Version">King James Version</a>), London: <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Imprinted at London by">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"> </span> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Barker_(printer)" class="extiw" title="w:Robert Barker (printer)">Robert Barker</a>,<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="printer to the Kings Most Excellent Maiestie.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span>, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/964384981">→OCLC</a></small>, <span class="None" lang="und"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acts_of_the_Apostles" class="extiw" title="w:Acts of the Apostles">Acts</a> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.kingjamesbibleonline.org/1611_Acts-Chapter-27/#41">27:41</a></span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">They <b>ran</b> the ship aground.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1691</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ray" class="extiw" title="w:John Ray">John Ray</a>, <cite>The Wisdom of God Manifested in the Works of the Creation</cite>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">[...]besides all this, a talkative person must needs be impertinent, and speak many idle words, and so render himself burdensome and odious to Company, and may perchance <b>run</b> himself upon great Inconveniences, by blabbing out his own or other’s Secrets;</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1706</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Locke" class="extiw" title="w:John Locke">John Locke</a>, <cite>Of the Conduct of the Understanding</cite>‎<sup><a class="external autonumber" href="https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Of_the_Conduct_of_the_Understanding">[8]</a></sup>, Section 24. Partiality:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">[...]and others, accustomed to retired speculations, <b>run</b> natural philosophy into metaphysical notions and the abstract generalities of logic ;</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To cause to be drawn; to mark out; to indicate; to determine.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> a line</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li>To encounter or incur (a danger or risk).
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">to <b>run</b> the risk of losing one's life</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1625</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Bacon" class="extiw" title="w:Francis Bacon">Francis [Bacon</a>], “Of Friendship”, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Essays_(Francis_Bacon)" class="extiw" title="w:Essays (Francis Bacon)">The Essayes<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="or Counsels, Civill and Moral, of Francis Lo[rd] Verulam, Viscount St. Alban. Newly Written.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></a></cite>, 3rd edition, London: <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Printed by">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"> </span> Iohn Haviland for Hanna Barret, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/863521290">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">He <b>runneth</b> two dangers.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To put at hazard; to venture; to risk.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1702–1704</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Hyde,_1st_Earl_of_Clarendon" class="extiw" title="w:Edward Hyde, 1st Earl of Clarendon">Edward [Hyde, 1st] Earl of Clarendon</a>, “<span class="maintenance-line" style="color: #777777;">(please specify |book=I to XVI)</span>”, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_History_of_the_Rebellion" class="extiw" title="w:The History of the Rebellion">The History of the Rebellion and Civil Wars in England, Begun in the Year 1641.<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="With the Precedent Passages, and Actions, that Contributed thereunto, and the Happy End, and Conclusion thereof by the King’s Blessed Restoration, and Return, upon the 29th of May, in the Year 1660. Written by the Right Honourable Edward Earl of Clarendon, Late Lord High Chancellor of England, Privy Counsellor in the Reigns of King Charles the First and the Second.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></a></cite>, Oxford, Oxfordshire: Printed at the Theater, published <span class="None" lang="und">1707</span>, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/937919305">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">He would himself be in the Highlands to receive them, and <b>run</b> his fortune with them.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To tease with sarcasms and ridicule.</li>
<li>To sew (a seam) by passing the needle through material in a continuous line, generally taking a series of stitches on the needle at the same time.</li>
<li>To control or have precedence in a card game.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Every three or four hands he would <b>run</b> the table.</i></div></dd></dl></li>
<li>To be in form thus, as a combination of words.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1722</b></span> [<span class="None" lang="und">1647</span>], <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Sanderson_(theologian)" class="extiw" title="w:Robert Sanderson (theologian)">Robert Sanderson</a>, translated by Thomas Lewis, <cite>A Preservative Against Schism and Rebellion, in the Most Trying Times</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=_VjK40EN_4kC&amp;pg=RA1-PA355">[9]</a></sup>, volume 1, translation of <cite>De juramenti promissorii obligatione</cite>, page <span class="None" lang="und">355</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Which Sovereignty, with us, ſo undoubtedly reſideth in the Perſon of the King, that his ordinary Style <b>runneth</b> — <i>Our Sovereign Lord the King:</i> <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b">[</span>…<span class="q-hellip-b">]</span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1922</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Travers" class="extiw" title="w:Ben Travers">Ben Travers</a>, chapter 5, in <cite>A Cuckoo in the Nest</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="http://openlibrary.org/works/OL1521052W">[10]</a></sup>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">The departure was not unduly prolonged. In the road Mr. Love and the driver favoured the company with a brief chanty <b>running</b>: “Got it?—No, I ain't, 'old on,—Got it? Got it?—No, 'old on sir.”</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><span class="see-cites">For more quotations using this term, see <a href="/wiki/Citations:run#English" title="Citations:run">Citations:run</a>.</span></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#archaic" title="Appendix:Glossary">archaic</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To be popularly known; to be generally received.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><i><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#c." title="Appendix:Glossary"><abbr title="circa">c.</abbr></a></i> <span class="None" lang="und"><b>1685</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sir_William_Temple,_1st_Baronet" class="extiw" title="w:Sir William Temple, 1st Baronet">William Temple</a>, <cite>Upon the Gardens of Epicurus</cite>‎<sup><a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="https://archive.org/details/sirwilliamtempl00tempuoft/page/26/mode/2up/">[11]</a></sup>, published <span class="None" lang="und">1908</span>, page <span class="None" lang="und">27</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">[...]great captains, and even consular men, who first brought them over, took pride in giving them their own names (by which they <b>run</b> a great while in Rome)</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1603</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Knolles" class="extiw" title="w:Richard Knolles">Richard Knolles</a>, <cite>The Generall Historie of the Turkes,<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="from the First Beginning of that Nation to the Rising of the Othoman Familie: With All the Notable Expeditions of the Christian Princes against Them. Together with the Lives and Conquests of the Othoman Kings and Emperours: Faithfullie Collected out of the Best Histories, both Auntient and Moderne, and Digested into One Continuat Historie vntill This Present Yeare 1603: By Richard Knolles">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></cite>, London: <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Printed by">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"> </span> Adam Islip, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/837543169">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Neither was he ignorant what report <b>ran</b> of himselfe.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To have growth or development.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Boys and girls <b>run</b> up rapidly.</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1707</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Mortimer_(agriculturalist)" class="extiw" title="w:John Mortimer (agriculturalist)">J[ohn] Mortimer</a>, <cite>The Whole Art of Husbandry; or, The Way of Managing and Improving of Land.<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Being a Full Collection of what hath been Writ, either by Ancient or Modern Authors: With Many Additions of New Experiments and Improvements Not Treated of by any Others. As also, an Account of the Particular Sorts of Husbandry Used in Several Counties; with Proposals for Its Farther Improvement. To which is Added, the Country-man’s Kalendar, what He is to Do Every Month in the Year.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></cite>, 2nd edition, London: <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Printed by">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"> </span> J<span style="font-style: normal;">[</span>ohn<span style="font-style: normal;">]</span> H<span style="font-style: normal;">[</span>umphreys<span style="font-style: normal;">]</span> for H<span style="font-style: normal;">[</span>enry<span style="font-style: normal;">]</span> Mortlock<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="at the Phœnix">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span>, and J<span style="font-style: normal;">[</span>onathan<span style="font-style: normal;">]</span> Robinson<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="at the Golden Lion in St. Paul’s Church-Yard">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span>, published <span class="None" lang="und">1708</span>, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/13320837">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">or the Richness of the Ground cause them [turnips] to <b>run</b> too much to Leaves</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To tend, as to an effect or consequence; to incline.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1625</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Bacon" class="extiw" title="w:Francis Bacon">Francis [Bacon</a>], “Of Nature in Men”, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Essays_(Francis_Bacon)" class="extiw" title="w:Essays (Francis Bacon)">The Essayes<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="or Counsels, Civill and Moral, of Francis Lo[rd] Verulam, Viscount St. Alban. Newly Written.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></a></cite>, 3rd edition, London: <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Printed by">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"> </span> Iohn Haviland for Hanna Barret, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/863521290">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">A man's nature <b>runs</b> either to herbs or weeds.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li>
<li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1708</b></span>, Jonathan Swift, “The Sentiments of a Church-of-England Man with respect to Religion and Government”, in <cite>The Works of Dr. Jonathan Swift</cite>, published <span class="None" lang="und">1757</span>, page <span class="None" lang="und">235</span>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">It hath been observed, that the temperate climates usually <b>run</b> into moderate governments, and the extremes into despotic power.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To have a legal course; to be attached; to continue in force, effect, or operation; to follow; to go in company.
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Certain covenants <b>run</b> with the land.</i></div></dd></dl>
<ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><i><a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#c." title="Appendix:Glossary"><abbr title="circa">c.</abbr></a></i> <span class="None" lang="und"><b>1665</b></span>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josiah_Child" class="extiw" title="w:Josiah Child">Josiah Child</a>, <cite>Discourse on Trade</cite>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Customs <b>run</b> only upon our goods imported or exported, and that but once for all; whereas interest <b>runs</b> as well upon our ships as goods, and must be yearly paid.</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li>To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/encounter#English" title="encounter">encounter</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/suffer#English" title="suffer">suffer</a> (a particular, usually bad, <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/fate#English" title="fate">fate</a> or <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/misfortune#English" title="misfortune">misfortune</a>).
<span class="HQToggle" style="margin-left: 5px;"><a role="button" tabindex="0">quotations&nbsp;▼</a></span><ul style="display: none;"><li><div class="citation-whole"><span class="cited-source"><span class="None" lang="und"><b>1748</b></span>, [<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Richardson" class="extiw" title="w:Samuel Richardson">Samuel Richardson</a>], chapter 8, in <cite><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarissa" class="extiw" title="w:Clarissa">Clarissa. Or, The History of a Young Lady:<span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Comprehending the Most Important Concerns of Private Life. And Particularly Shewing, the Distresses that may Attend the Misconduct both of Parents and Children, in Relation to Marriage.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span></a></cite>, volume I, London: <span class="q-hellip-sp"> </span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="Printed for">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"> </span> S<span style="font-style: normal;">[</span>amuel<span style="font-style: normal;">]</span> Richardson; <span class="q-hellip-sp">&nbsp;</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">[</span></span><span title="And sold by A[ndrew] Millar, over-against Catharine-street in the Strand; J[ohn] and Ja[mes] Rivington, in St. Paul’s Church-yard; John Osborn, in Pater-noster Row; [a]nd by J. Leake, at Bath.">…</span><span class="q-hellip-b"><span style="font-style: normal;">]</span></span><span class="q-hellip-b"></span>, <small><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.worldcat.org/title/13631815">→OCLC</a></small>:</span><dl><dd><div class="h-quotation"><span class="Latn e-quotation cited-passage" lang="en">Don't let me <b>run</b> the fate of all who show indulgence to your sex […].</span></div></dd></dl></div></li></ul></li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/golf#English" title="golf">golf</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To strike (the ball) in such a way as to cause it to run along the ground, as when approaching a hole.</li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/video_game#English" title="video game">video games</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> <a href="/wiki/Appendix:Glossary#rare" title="Appendix:Glossary">rare</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <span class="Latn" lang="en"><a href="/wiki/speedrun#English" title="speedrun">speedrun</a></span>.</li>
<li><span class="usage-label-sense"><span class="ib-brac">(</span><span class="ib-content"><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/sports#English" title="sports">sports</a><span class="ib-comma">,</span> especially <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/baseball#English" title="baseball">baseball</a></span><span class="ib-brac">)</span></span> To <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/eject#English" title="eject">eject</a> from a game or match.
<dl><dd><div class="h-usage-example"><i class="Latn mention e-example" lang="en">Jackson got himself <b>run</b> in the top of the sixth for arguing a borderline strike three call.</i></div></dd></dl></li></ol>

literally, formally, slang)</p><p style="display: block;"><a href="/wiki/Wiktionary:List_of_scripts">Script code</a>: <input name="sc" size="6" title="The script code to apply to this word.">(e.g. Cyrl for Cyrillic, Latn for Latin)<br></p><p style="display: none;">Nesting: <input name="nested" title="The nesting of this language"> (e.g. Serbo-Croatian/Cyrillic)</p><span></span></form></li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>
